{
  "query": "How do different management approaches for uncropped arable field margins in Europe, such as sowing mixes versus natural regeneration, compare in their benefits for bumblebees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Five replicated trials in Europe showed that sowing uncropped arable field margins with an agricultural nectar and pollen mix, particularly those containing perennial leguminous flowering plants, attracted significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated margins (18). Similarly, five replicated trials in the UK indicated that margins sown with native wild flower seed mixes supported a higher abundance of foraging bumblebees compared to naturally regenerated uncropped margins (19). One small trial, however, recorded the same number of bee species on both wildflower sown and naturally regenerated strips (19).\n\nThree replicated trials found that a mix of agricultural forage plants attracted a greater number of bumblebees than a perennial wildflower mix, at least in the first year (18). Conversely, one small replicated trial showed that common long-tongued bumblebee species strongly preferred perennial wildflower seed mixes over a mix of annual forage plants (19). Perennial leguminous herbs in wildflower seed mixtures were noted as important forage sources for bumblebees, especially long-tongued species (19).\n\nRegarding naturally regenerated margins, four replicated trials in the UK found more bumblebees foraging on these compared to cropped margins (20). However, the value of these margins for bees was not consistent from year to year and often relied on thistle species considered to be pernicious weeds (20). A small replicated trial found that neither the abundance nor diversity of bumblebees was higher on naturally regenerated margins than on cropped margins (20).\n\nFinally, three trials in the UK found that margins sown with agricultural legume plants degraded in their value to bumblebees and would require re-sowing every few years (18). For all three management approaches\u2014sowing with agricultural mixes, sowing with wildflower mixes, and natural regeneration\u2014no evidence was captured on the effects on solitary bees (18, 19, 20).",
