{
  "query": "risks and control methods associated with using commercial bee colonies for pollination",
  "relevant_summary": "Parasites and pathogens are a known risk when commercially rearing and managing solitary bee populations for pollination, and various control methods have been developed (54). There are also risks associated with feeding bees artificial diets. One replicated trial showed high larval mortality in Osmia cornuta when they were reared on artificial pollen-based diets, which included pollen collected by honey bees. Another trial found that Megachile rotundata either died or had low pre-pupal weight when reared on synthetic pollen substitutes (54). However, M. rotundata could be successfully reared on an artificial diet that was based on honey bee-collected pollen (54). In times of pollen scarcity, stingless bees (Scaptotrigona postica) can be fed pollen substitutes such as brewer's yeast or a mixture with 25% pollen collected by honey bees (33). To avoid damaging the brood during honey extraction, a wooden hive with separate, different-shaped honey and brood chambers can be used (33). Additionally, brood growth in traditional log hives was found to be higher than in box hives with internal volumes exceeding 14 litres, leading to a recommendation for smaller box hives (33).",
