{
  "query": "What unintended negative consequences or limitations have been identified when providing artificial nest boxes for bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several unintended negative consequences and limitations have been identified with the provision of artificial nest boxes for bees. Parasitism and predation are potential negative consequences of providing artificial nest boxes (47). Mortality rates from these causes have been measured at between 13% and 56% (47). Additionally, some nest box designs, such as those with plastic-lined holes or plastic/paper tubes, have been found to be less productive due to issues with parasitism or mould (47). Another unintended consequence is the occupation of nest boxes by non-native species, which in some cases, used the boxes more commonly than native bees (47).\n\nA significant limitation is the low uptake or occupancy rate of the nest boxes (48, 80). For bumblebees, very low uptake rates of 0-2.5% have been recorded in several UK trials (48, 80). Similarly, some trials for solitary bees have shown no occupancy at all (47). Furthermore, for bumblebees, there is no evidence to suggest that providing nest boxes has a positive effect on their populations (48). Commonly marketed wooden surface or above-ground nest boxes are not the most effective designs for bumblebees and have resulted in occupancy rates as low as 0-1.5% in some UK studies (48).",
  "action_ids": [
    "47",
